# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biological-organisation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:biological-organisation/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:biological-organisation/abiotic] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:biological-organisation/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:biological-organisation/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea were initially classified as bacteria, receiving the name archaebacteria (/ˌɑːrkibækˈtɪəriə/, in the Archaebacteria kingdom), but this term has fallen out of use.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaeal cells have unique properties distinguishing them from Bacteria and Eukaryota, including: cell membranes made of ether-linked lipids; metabolisms such as methanogenesis; and a unique motility structure known as an archaellum.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are further divided into multiple recognized phyla.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Classification is difficult because most have not been isolated in a laboratory and have been identified only by their gene sequences in environmental samples.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] They have not been observed to produce endospores.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are often similar to bacteria in size and shape, although a few have very different shapes, such as the flat, square cells of *Haloquadratum walsbyi*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Despite this, archaea possess genes and several metabolic pathways that are more closely related to those of eukaryotes, notably for the enzymes involved in transcription and translation.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other aspects of archaeal biochemistry are unique, such as their reliance on ether lipids in their cell membranes, including archaeols.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea use more diverse energy sources than eukaryotes, ranging from organic compounds such as sugars, to ammonia, metal ions or even hydrogen gas.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The salt-tolerant Halobacteria use sunlight as an energy source, and other species of archaea fix carbon (autotrophy), but unlike cyanobacteria, no known species of archaea does both.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary fission, fragmentation, or budding; unlike bacteria, no known species of Archaea form endospores.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The first observed archaea were extremophiles, living in extreme environments such as hot springs and salt lakes with no other organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Improved molecular detection tools led to the discovery of archaea in almost every habitat, including soil, oceans, and marshlands.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are particularly numerous in the oceans, and the archaea in plankton may be one of the most abundant groups of organisms on the planet.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are a major part of Earth's life.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] They are part of the microbiota of all organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In the human microbiome, they are important in the gut, mouth, and on the skin.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Their morphological, metabolic, and geographical diversity permits them to play multiple ecological roles: carbon fixation; nitrogen cycling; organic compound turnover; and maintaining microbial symbiotic and syntrophic communities, for example.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] As of 2024, only one species of archaea has been found to be parasitic; many are mutualists or commensals, such as the methanogens (methane-producers) that inhabit the gastrointestinal tract in humans and ruminants, where their vast numbers facilitate digestion.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Methanogens are used in biogas production and sewage treatment, while biotechnology exploits enzymes from extremophile archaea that can endure high temperatures and organic solvents.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] For much of the 20th century, prokaryotes were regarded as a single group of organisms and classified based on their biochemistry, morphology and metabolism.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Microbiologists tried to classify microorganisms based on the structures of their cell walls, their shapes, and the substances they consume.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In 1965, Emile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling instead proposed using the sequences of the genes in different prokaryotes to work out how they are related to each other.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This phylogenetic approach is the main method used today.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The first archaea to be isolated and grown in pure culture were methane-producing species in the genera Methanobacterium and Methanococcus in the 1930s and 1940s, although at the time, they were classified as bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea were first classified separately from bacteria in 1977 by Carl Woese and George E.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Fox, based on their ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] (At that time only the methanogens were known).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] They called these groups the *Urkingdoms* of Archaebacteria and Eubacteria, though other researchers treated them as kingdoms or subkingdoms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Woese and Fox gave the first evidence for Archaebacteria as a separate "line of descent": 1. lack of peptidoglycan in their cell walls, 2. two unusual coenzymes, 3. results of 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequencing.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] To emphasize this difference, Woese, Otto Kandler and Mark Wheelis later proposed reclassifying organisms into three then thought to be natural domains known as the three-domain system: the Eukarya, the Bacteria and the Archaea, in what is now known as the Woesian Revolution.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Extreme halophilic and hyperthermophilic microbes were also included in Archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] For a long time, archaea were seen as extremophiles that exist only in extreme habitats such as hot springs and salt lakes, but by the end of the 20th century, archaea had been identified in non-extreme environments as well.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Today, they are known to be a large and diverse group of organisms abundantly distributed throughout nature.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This new appreciation of the importance and ubiquity of archaea came from using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to detect prokaryotes from environmental samples (such as water or soil) by multiplying their ribosomal genes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This allows the detection and identification of organisms that have not been cultured in the laboratory.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea, and of prokaryotes in general, is a rapidly moving and contentious field.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Current classification systems aim to organize archaea into groups of organisms that share structural features and common ancestors.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These classifications rely heavily on the use of the sequence of ribosomal RNA genes to reveal relationships among organisms (molecular phylogenetics).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Most of the culturable and well-investigated species of archaea are members of two main kingdoms, the Methanobacteriati and the Thermoproteati (formerly TACK).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other groups have been tentatively created, such as the peculiar species *Nanoarchaeum equitans* – discovered in 2003 and assigned its own phylum, the Nanoarchaeota (reassigned to Nanobdellota in 2023).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] A new phylum "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) has also been proposed, containing a small group of unusual thermophilic species sharing features of both the main phyla.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other detected species of archaea are only distantly related to any of these groups, such as the Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising Micrarchaeota and Parvarchaeota), which were discovered in 2006 and are some of the smallest organisms known.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] A superphylum – "TACK" (now kingdom Thermoproteati) – which includes the Thaumarchaeota (now Nitrososphaerota), "Augarchaeota", Crenarchaeota (now Thermoproteota), and "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) was proposed in 2011 to be related to the origin of eukaryotes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In 2017, the newly discovered and newly named "Asgard" (now kingdom Promethearchaeati) superphylum was proposed to be more closely related to the original eukaryote and a sister group to Thermoproteati / "TACK".
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In 2013, the superphylum "DPANN" (now kingdom Nanobdellati) was proposed to group "Nanoarchaeota", "Nanohaloarchaeota", Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising "Micrarchaeota" and "Parvarchaeota"), and other similar archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This archaeal superphylum encompasses at least 10 different lineages and includes organisms with extremely small cell and genome sizes and limited metabolic capabilities.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Therefore, Nanobdellati/"DPANN" may include members obligately dependent on symbiotic interactions, and may even include novel parasites.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] However, other phylogenetic analyses found that Nanobdellati/"DPANN" does not form a monophyletic group, and that the apparent grouping is caused by long branch attraction (LBA), suggesting that all these lineages belong to Methanobacteriati.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea into species is also controversial.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Ernst Mayr's species definition – a reproductively isolated group of interbreeding organisms - does not apply, as archaea reproduce only asexually.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea show high levels of horizontal gene transfer between lineages.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some researchers suggest that individuals can be grouped into species-like populations given highly similar genomes and infrequent gene transfer to/from cells with less-related genomes, as in the genus *Ferroplasma*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] On the other hand, studies in *Halorubrum* found significant genetic transfer to/from less-related populations, limiting the criterion's applicability.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some researchers question whether such species designations have practical meaning.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Current knowledge on genetic diversity in archaeans is fragmentary, so the total number of species cannot be estimated with any accuracy.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Estimates of the number of phyla range from 18 to 23, of which only 8 have representatives that have been cultured and studied directly.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Many of these hypothesized groups are known from a single rRNA sequence, so the level of diversity remains obscure.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This situation is also seen in the Bacteria; many uncultured microbes present similar issues with characterization.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The age of the Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Scientific evidence suggests that life began on Earth at least 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The earliest evidence for life on Earth is graphite found to be biogenic in 3.7-billion-year-old metasedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland and microbial mat fossils found in 3.48-billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In 2015, possible remains of biotic matter were found in 4.1-billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Although probable prokaryotic cell fossils date to almost 3.5 billion years ago, most prokaryotes do not have distinctive morphologies, and fossil shapes cannot be used to identify them as archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Instead, chemical fossils of unique lipids are more informative because such compounds do not occur in other organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some publications suggest that archaeal or eukaryotic lipid remains are present in shales dating from 2.7 billion years ago, though such data have since been questioned.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These lipids have also been detected in even older rocks from west Greenland.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The oldest such traces come from the Isua district, which includes Earth's oldest known sediments, formed 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The archaeal lineage may be the most ancient that exists on Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Woese argued that the bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes represent separate lines of descent that diverged early on from an ancestral colony of organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] One possibility is that this occurred before the evolution of cells, when the lack of a typical cell membrane allowed unrestricted lateral gene transfer, and that the common ancestors of the three domains arose by fixation of specific subsets of genes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] It is possible that the last common ancestor of bacteria and archaea was a thermophile, which raises the possibility that lower temperatures are "extreme environments" for archaea, and organisms that live in cooler environments appeared only later.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Since archaea and bacteria are no more related to each other than they are to eukaryotes, the term *prokaryote* may suggest a false similarity between them.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] However, structural and functional similarities between lineages often occur because of shared ancestral traits or evolutionary convergence.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These similarities are known as a *grade*, and prokaryotes are best thought of as a grade of life, characterized by such features as an absence of membrane-bound organelles.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The following table compares some major characteristics of the three domains, to illustrate their similarities and differences.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea were split off as a third domain because of the large differences in their ribosomal RNA structure.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The particular molecule 16S rRNA is key to the production of proteins in all organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Because this function is so central to life, organisms with mutations in their 16S rRNA are unlikely to survive, leading to great (but not absolute) stability in the structure of this polynucleotide over generations.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] 16S rRNA is large enough to show organism-specific variations, but still small enough to be compared quickly.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In 1977, Carl Woese, a microbiologist studying the genetic sequences of organisms, developed a new comparison method that involved splitting the RNA into fragments that could be sorted and compared with other fragments from other organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The more similar the patterns between species, the more closely they are related.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Woese used his new rRNA comparison method to categorize and contrast different organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] He compared a variety of species and happened upon a group of methanogens with rRNA vastly different from any known prokaryotes or eukaryotes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These methanogens were much more similar to each other than to other organisms, leading Woese to propose the new domain of Archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] His experiments showed that the archaea were genetically more similar to eukaryotes than prokaryotes, even though they were more similar to prokaryotes in structure.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This led to the conclusion that Archaea and Eukarya shared a common ancestor more recent than Eukarya and Bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The development of the nucleus occurred after the split between Bacteria and this common ancestor.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] One property unique to archaea is the abundant use of ether-linked lipids in their cell membranes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Ether linkages are more chemically stable than the ester linkages found in bacteria and eukarya, which may be a contributing factor to the ability of many archaea to survive in extreme environments that place heavy stress on cell membranes, such as extreme heat and salinity.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Comparative analysis of archaeal genomes has also identified several molecular conserved signature indels and signature proteins uniquely present in either all archaea or different main groups within archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Another unique feature of archaea, found in no other organisms, is methanogenesis (the metabolic production of methane).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Methanogenic archaea play a pivotal role in ecosystems with organisms that derive energy from oxidation of methane, many of which are bacteria, as they are often a major source of methane in such environments and can play a role as primary producers.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Methanogens also play a critical role in the carbon cycle, breaking down organic carbon into methane, which is also a major greenhouse gas.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This difference in the biochemical structure of Bacteria and Archaea has been explained by researchers through evolutionary processes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] It is theorized that both domains originated at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] At least twice, microbes evolved lipid biosynthesis and cell wall biochemistry.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] It has been suggested that the last universal common ancestor was a non-free-living organism.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] It may have had a permeable membrane composed of bacterial simple chain amphiphiles (fatty acids), including archaeal simple chain amphiphiles (isoprenoids).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These stabilize fatty acid membranes in seawater; this property may have driven the divergence of bacterial and archaeal membranes, "with the later biosynthesis of phospholipids giving rise to the unique G1P and G3P headgroups of archaea and bacteria respectively.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] If so, the properties conferred by membrane isoprenoids place the lipid divide as early as the origin of life".
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The relationships among the three domains are of central importance for understanding the origin of life.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Most of the metabolic pathways, which are the object of the majority of an organism's genes, are common between Archaea and Bacteria, while most genes involved in gene expression are common between Archaea and Eukarya.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Within prokaryotes, archaeal cell structure is most similar to that of Gram-positive bacteria, largely because both have a single lipid bilayer and usually contain a thick sacculus (exoskeleton) of varying chemical composition.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In some phylogenetic trees based upon different gene / protein sequences of prokaryotic homologs, the archaeal homologs are more closely related to those of gram-positive bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea and gram-positive bacteria also share conserved indels in a number of important proteins, such as Hsp70 and glutamine synthetase I; but the phylogeny of these genes was interpreted to reveal inter-domain gene transfer, and might not reflect the organismal relationship(s).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] It has been proposed that the archaea evolved from Gram-positive bacteria in response to antibiotic selection pressure.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This is suggested by the observation that archaea are resistant to a wide variety of antibiotics that are produced primarily by Gram-positive bacteria, and that these antibiotics act primarily on the genes that distinguish archaea from bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The proposal is that the selective pressure towards resistance generated by the gram-positive antibiotics was eventually sufficient to cause extensive changes in many of the antibiotics' target genes, and that these strains represented the common ancestors of present-day Archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This proposal is also supported by other work investigating protein structural relationships and studies that suggest that gram-positive bacteria may constitute the earliest branching lineages within the prokaryotes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The evolutionary relationship between archaea and eukaryotes remains unclear.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Aside from the similarities in cell structure and function that are discussed below, many genetic trees group the two.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The standard hypothesis states that the ancestor of the eukaryotes diverged early from the Archaea, and that eukaryotes arose through symbiogenesis, the fusion of an archaean and a eubacterium, which formed the mitochondria; this hypothesis explains the genetic similarities between the groups.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The eocyte hypothesis instead posits that Eukaryota emerged relatively late from the Archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] A lineage of archaea discovered in 2015, *Lokiarchaeum* (of the proposed new phylum "Lokiarchaeota"), named for a hydrothermal vent called Loki's Castle in the Arctic Ocean, was found to be the most closely related to eukaryotes known at that time.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] It has been called a transitional organism between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Several sister phyla of "Lokiarchaeota" have since been found ("Thorarchaeota", "Odinarchaeota", "Heimdallarchaeota"), all together comprising a newly proposed supergroup "Asgard".
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea range from 0.1 micrometers (μm) to over 15 μm in diameter, and commonly occur as spheres, rods, spirals or plates.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Morphologies in the Thermoproteota also include irregularly shaped lobed cells in *Sulfolobus*, needle-like filaments that are less than half a micrometer in diameter in *Thermofilum*, and almost perfectly rectangular rods in *Thermoproteus* and *Pyrobaculum*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Haloquadratum* such as *Haloquadratum walsbyi* are flat, square specimens that live in hypersaline pools.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These unusual shapes are probably maintained by both their cell walls and a prokaryotic cytoskeleton.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Proteins related to the cytoskeleton components of other organisms exist in archaea, and filaments form within their cells, but in contrast with other organisms, these cellular structures are poorly understood.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma* the lack of a cell wall means that the cells have irregular shapes, and can resemble amoebae.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some species form aggregates or filaments of cells up to 200 μm long.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These organisms can be prominent in biofilms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Notably, aggregates of *Thermococcus coalescens* cells fuse together in culture, forming single giant cells.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Pyrodictium* produce an elaborate multicell colony involving arrays of long, thin hollow tubes called *cannulae* that stick out from the cells' surfaces and connect them into a dense bush-like agglomeration.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The function of these cannulae is not settled, but they may allow communication or nutrient exchange with neighbors.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Multi-species colonies exist, such as the "string-of-pearls" community that was discovered in 2001 in a German swamp.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Round whitish colonies of a novel Methanobacteriati species are spaced along thin filaments that can range up to 15 centimetres (5.9 in) long; these filaments are made of a particular bacteria species.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea and bacteria have generally similar cell structure, but cell composition and organization set the archaea apart.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, archaea lack interior membranes and organelles.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, the cell membranes of archaea are usually bounded by a cell wall and they swim using one or more flagella.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Structurally, archaea are most similar to gram-positive bacteria.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Most have a single plasma membrane and cell wall, and lack a periplasmic space; the exception to this general rule is *Ignicoccus*, which possess a particularly large periplasm that contains membrane-bound vesicles and is enclosed by an outer membrane.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Most archaea (but not *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma*) possess a cell wall.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In most archaea, the wall is assembled from surface-layer proteins, which form an S-layer.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] An S-layer is a rigid array of protein molecules that cover the outside of the cell (like chain mail).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This layer provides both chemical and physical protection, and can prevent macromolecules from contacting the cell membrane.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Unlike bacteria, archaea lack peptidoglycan in their cell walls.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaeal flagella are known as archaella, that operate like bacterial flagella – their long stalks are driven by rotatory motors at the base.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These motors are powered by a proton gradient across the membrane, but archaella are notably different in composition and development.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The two types of flagella evolved from different ancestors.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The bacterial flagellum shares a common ancestor with the type III secretion system, while archaeal flagella appear to have evolved from bacterial type IV pili.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In contrast with the bacterial flagellum, which is hollow and assembled by subunits moving up the central pore to the tip of the flagella, archaeal flagella are synthesized by adding subunits at the base.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaeal membranes are made of different molecules from those in bacterial and eukaryotic membranes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In all organisms, cell membranes are made of molecules known as phospholipids.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These molecules possess both a polar part that dissolves in water (the phosphate "head"), and a "greasy" non-polar part that does not (the lipid tail).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These dissimilar parts are connected by a glycerol moiety.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In water, phospholipids cluster, with the heads facing the water and the tails facing away from it.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The major structure in cell membranes is a double layer of these phospholipids, which is called a lipid bilayer.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea exhibit a great variety of chemical reactions in their metabolism and use many sources of energy.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These reactions are classified into nutritional groups, depending on energy and carbon sources.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some archaea obtain energy from inorganic compounds such as sulfur or ammonia (they are chemotrophs).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These include nitrifiers, methanogens and anaerobic methane oxidisers.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In these reactions, one compound passes electrons to another (in a redox reaction), releasing energy to fuel the cell's activities.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] One compound acts as an electron donor and one as an electron acceptor.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The energy released is used to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP) through chemiosmosis, the same basic process that happens in the mitochondrion of eukaryotic cells.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other groups of archaea use sunlight as a source of energy (they are phototrophs), but oxygen–generating photosynthesis does not occur in any of these organisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Many basic metabolic pathways are shared among all forms of life; for example, archaea use a modified form of glycolysis (the Entner–Doudoroff pathway) and either a complete or partial citric acid cycle.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These similarities to other organisms probably reflect both early origins in the history of life and their high level of efficiency.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some Methanobacteriati are methanogens (archaea that produce methane as a result of metabolism) living in anaerobic environments, such as swamps.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This form of metabolism evolved early, and it is even possible that the first free-living organism was a methanogen.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] A common reaction involves the use of carbon dioxide as an electron acceptor to oxidize hydrogen.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Methanogenesis involves a range of coenzymes that are unique to these archaea, such as coenzyme M and methanofuran.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other organic compounds such as alcohols, acetic acid or formic acid are used as alternative electron acceptors by methanogens.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These reactions are common in gut-dwelling archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Acetic acid is also broken down into methane and carbon dioxide directly, by *acetotrophic* archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These acetotrophs are archaea in the order Methanosarcinales, and are a major part of the communities of microorganisms that produce biogas.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other archaea use CO 2 in the atmosphere as a source of carbon, in a process called carbon fixation (they are autotrophs).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This process involves either a highly modified form of the Calvin cycle or another metabolic pathway called the 3-hydroxypropionate / 4-hydroxybutyrate cycle.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The Thermoproteota also use the reverse Krebs cycle while the Methanobacteriati also use the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Carbon fixation is powered by inorganic energy sources.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] No known archaea carry out photosynthesis.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaeal energy sources are extremely diverse, and range from the oxidation of ammonia by the Nitrosopumilales to the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide or elemental sulfur by species of *Sulfolobus*, using either oxygen or metal ions as electron acceptors.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Phototrophic archaea use light to produce chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In the Halobacteria, light-activated ion pumps like bacteriorhodopsin and halorhodopsin generate ion gradients by pumping ions out of and into the cell across the plasma membrane.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The energy stored in these electrochemical gradients is then converted into ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This process is a form of photophosphorylation.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The ability of these light-driven pumps to move ions across membranes depends on light-driven changes in the structure of a retinol cofactor buried in the center of the protein.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea usually have a single circular chromosome, but many euryarchaea have been shown to bear multiple copies of this chromosome.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The largest known archaeal genome as of 2002 was 5,751,492 base pairs in *Methanosarcina acetivorans*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The tiny 490,885 base-pair genome of *Nanoarchaeum equitans* is one-tenth of this size and the smallest archaeal genome known; it is estimated to contain only 537 protein-encoding genes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Smaller independent pieces of DNA, called *plasmids*, are also found in archaea.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Plasmids may be transferred between cells by physical contact, in a process that may be similar to bacterial conjugation.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are genetically distinct from bacteria and eukaryotes, with up to 15% of the proteins encoded by any one archaeal genome being unique to the domain, although most of these unique genes have no known function.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Of the remainder of the unique proteins that have an identified function, most belong to the Methanobacteriati and are involved in methanogenesis.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The proteins that archaea, bacteria and eukaryotes share form a common core of cell function, relating mostly to transcription, translation, and nucleotide metabolism.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other characteristic archaeal features are the organization of genes of related function – such as enzymes that catalyze steps in the same metabolic pathway into novel operons, and large differences in tRNA genes and their aminoacyl tRNA synthetases.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Transcription in archaea more closely resembles eukaryotic than bacterial transcription, with the archaeal RNA polymerase being very close to its equivalent in eukaryotes, while archaeal translation shows signs of both bacterial and eukaryotic equivalents.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Post-transcriptional modification is simpler than in eukaryotes, since most archaeal genes lack introns, although there are many introns in their transfer RNA and ribosomal RNA genes, and introns may occur in a few protein-encoding genes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] When the hyperthermophilic archaea *Sulfolobus solfataricus* and *Sulfolobus acidocaldarius* are exposed to DNA-damaging UV irradiation or to the agents bleomycin or mitomycin C, species-specific cellular aggregation is induced.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Aggregation in *S. solfataricus* could not be induced by other physical stressors, such as pH or temperature shift, suggesting that aggregation is induced specifically by DNA damage.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Ajon et al. showed that UV-induced cellular aggregation mediates chromosomal marker exchange with high frequency in *S. acidocaldarius*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Recombination rates exceeded those of uninduced cultures by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Frols et al. and Ajon et al. hypothesized that cellular aggregation enhances species-specific DNA transfer between *Sulfolobus* cells in order to provide increased repair of damaged DNA by means of homologous recombination.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This response may be a primitive form of sexual interaction similar to the more well-studied bacterial transformation systems that are also associated with species-specific DNA transfer between cells leading to homologous recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are the target of a number of viruses in a diverse virosphere distinct from bacterial and eukaryotic viruses.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] They have been organized into 15–18 DNA-based families so far, but multiple species remain un-isolated and await classification.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These families can be informally divided into two groups: archaea-specific and cosmopolitan.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaeal-specific viruses target only archaean species and currently include 12 families.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Numerous unique, previously unidentified viral structures have been observed in this group, including: bottle-shaped, spindle-shaped, coil-shaped, and droplet-shaped viruses.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] While the reproductive cycles and genomic mechanisms of archaea-specific species may be similar to other viruses, they bear unique characteristics that were specifically developed due to the morphology of host cells they infect.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Their virus release mechanisms differ from that of other phages.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Bacteriophages generally undergo either lytic pathways, lysogenic pathways, or (rarely) a mix of the two.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Most archaea-specific viral strains maintain a stable, somewhat lysogenic, relationship with their hosts – appearing as a chronic infection.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This involves the gradual, and continuous, production and release of virions without killing the host cell.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Prangishyili (2013) noted that it has been hypothesized that tailed archaeal phages originated from bacteriophages capable of infecting haloarchaeal species.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] If the hypothesis is correct, it can be concluded that other double-stranded DNA viruses that make up the rest of the archaea-specific group are their own unique group in the global viral community.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] (2018) states that the high levels of horizontal gene transfer, rapid mutation rates in viral genomes, and lack of universal gene sequences have led researchers to perceive the evolutionary pathway of archaeal viruses as a network.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The lack of similarities among phylogenetic markers in this network and the global virosphere, as well as external linkages to non-viral elements, may suggest that some species of archaea specific viruses evolved from non-viral mobile genetic elements (MGE).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These viruses have been studied in most detail in thermophilics, particularly the orders Sulfolobales and Thermoproteales.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Two groups of single-stranded DNA viruses that infect archaea have been recently isolated.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] One group is exemplified by the *Halorubrum pleomorphic virus 1* (*Pleolipoviridae*) infecting halophilic archaea, and the other one by the *Aeropyrum coil-shaped virus* (*Spiraviridae*) infecting a hyperthermophilic (optimal growth at 90–95 °C) host.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Notably, the latter virus has the largest currently reported ssDNA genome.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Defenses against these viruses may involve RNA interference from repetitive DNA sequences that are related to the genes of the viruses.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary or multiple fission, fragmentation, or budding; mitosis and meiosis do not occur, so if a species of archaea exists in more than one form, all have the same genetic material.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Cell division is controlled in a cell cycle; after the cell's chromosome is replicated and the two daughter chromosomes separate, the cell divides.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In the genus *Sulfolobus*, the cycle has characteristics that are similar to both bacterial and eukaryotic systems.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] The chromosomes replicate from multiple starting points (origins of replication) using DNA polymerases that resemble the equivalent eukaryotic enzymes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In Methanobacteriati the cell division protein FtsZ, which forms a contracting ring around the cell, and the components of the septum that is constructed across the center of the cell, are similar to their bacterial equivalents.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] In cren- and thaumarchaea, the cell division machinery Cdv fulfills a similar role.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] This machinery is related to the eukaryotic ESCRT-III machinery which, while best known for its role in cell sorting, also has been seen to fulfill a role in separation between divided cell, suggesting an ancestral role in cell division.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Both bacteria and eukaryotes, but not archaea, make spores.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing was originally thought to not exist in Archaea, but recent studies have shown evidence of some species being able to perform cross-talk through quorum sensing.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Other studies have shown syntrophic interactions between archaea and bacteria during biofilm growth.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Although research is limited in archaeal quorum sensing, some studies have uncovered LuxR proteins in archaeal species, displaying similarities with bacteria LuxR, and ultimately allowing for the detection of small molecules that are used in high density communication.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Similarly to bacteria, Archaea LuxR solos have shown to bind to AHLs (lactones) and non-AHLs ligans, which is a large part in performing intraspecies, interspecies, and interkingdom communication through quorum sensing.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Archaea are known to form biofilms, a common strategy among microorganisms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing is thought to play a role in Archaeal biofilm formation, but less is known about Archaeal quorum sensing than Bacterial quorum sensing.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some Archaea have been observed to form biofilms when the pH is a specific value, without necessarily relying on quorum sensing for instance.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] These biofilms are sessile communities of micro-organisms (they can contain multiple different species) that produce extracellular polymeric substances, which are used to create a matrix, within which the micro-organisms can grow.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Biofilms are beneficial as they: protect organisms from abiotic stresses; facilitate horizontal gene transfer; and enable syntropy to take place.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Biofilm formation has a number of stages: attachment; micro-colony formation; maturation; and dispersal.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] During the attachment phase the Archaea are reversibly attached to a surface by type-4 pili and archaella.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Some Archaea possess other structures involved in attachment such as hami; fimbriae; or cannulae.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] During the micro colony phase, the extracellular polymeric substance matrix is produced, and numerous archaea have been observed to produce pills and nanowires between cells.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] During the maturation phase the matrix takes on a sophisticated architecture, such as including pathways for waste to exit the biofilms.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Different archaea have been observed to produce biofilms with different architectures.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p01] Finally, dispersal can take place, where cells begin to leave the biofilm, this process has been observed in Archaea but the mechanisms behind it are not understood.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaea exist in a broad range of habitats, are recognized as a major part of global ecosystems, and may represent about 20% of microbial cells in the oceans as well as a large number of cells in sea floor sediment.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] However, the first-discovered archaeans were extremophiles.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Indeed, some archaea survive high temperatures, often above 100 °C (212 °F), as found in geysers, black smokers, and oil wells.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Other common habitats include very cold habitats and highly saline, acidic, or alkaline water, but archaea include mesophiles that grow in mild conditions, in swamps and marshland, sewage, the oceans, the intestinal tract of animals, and soils.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Similar to PGPR, Archaea are considered a source of plant growth promotion as well.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea are members of four main physiological groups.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] These are the halophiles, thermophiles, alkaliphiles, and acidophiles.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] These groups are not comprehensive or phylum-specific, nor are they mutually exclusive, since some archaea belong to several groups.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Nonetheless, they are a useful starting point for classification.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Halophiles, including the genus *Halobacterium*, live in extremely saline environments such as salt lakes and outnumber their bacterial counterparts at salinities greater than 20–25%.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Thermophiles grow best at temperatures above 45 °C (113 °F), in places such as hot springs; *hyperthermophilic* archaea grow optimally at temperatures greater than 80 °C (176 °F).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] The archaeal *Methanopyrus kandleri* Strain 116 can even reproduce at 122 °C (252 °F), the highest recorded temperature of any organism.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Other archaea exist in very acidic or alkaline conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] For example, one of the most extreme archaean acidophiles is *Picrophilus torridus*, which grows at pH 0, which is equivalent to thriving in 1.2 molar sulfuric acid.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] This resistance to extreme environments has made archaea the focus of speculation about the possible properties of extraterrestrial life.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Some extremophile habitats are not dissimilar to those on Mars, leading to the suggestion that viable microbes could be transferred between planets in meteorites.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Recently, several studies have shown that archaea exist not only in mesophilic and thermophilic environments but are also present, sometimes in high numbers, at low temperatures as well.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] For example, archaea are common in cold oceanic environments such as polar seas.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Even more significant are the large numbers of archaea found throughout the world's oceans in non-extreme habitats among the plankton community (as part of the picoplankton).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Although these archaea can be present in extremely high numbers (up to 40% of the microbial biomass), almost none of these species have been isolated and studied in pure culture.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Consequently, our understanding of the role of archaea in ocean ecology is rudimentary, so their full influence on global biogeochemical cycles remains largely unexplored.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Some marine Thermoproteota are capable of nitrification, suggesting these organisms may affect the oceanic nitrogen cycle, although these oceanic Thermoproteota may also use other sources of energy.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Vast numbers of archaea are also found in the sediments that cover the sea floor, with these organisms making up at least 12.8%, and in many places, the majority of living cells at depths over 1 meter below the ocean bottom.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaea recycle elements such as carbon, nitrogen, and sulfur through their various habitats.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaea carry out many steps in the nitrogen cycle.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] This includes both reactions that remove nitrogen from ecosystems (such as nitrate-based respiration and denitrification) as well as processes that introduce nitrogen (such as nitrate assimilation and nitrogen fixation).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Researchers recently discovered archaeal involvement in ammonia oxidation reactions.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] These reactions are particularly important in the oceans.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] The archaea also appear crucial for ammonia oxidation in soils.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] They produce nitrite, which other microbes then oxidize to nitrate.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Plants and other organisms consume the latter.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In the carbon cycle, methanogen archaea remove hydrogen and play an important role in the decay of organic matter by the populations of microorganisms that act as decomposers in anaerobic ecosystems, such as sediments, marshes, and sewage-treatment works.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] The well-characterized interactions between archaea and other organisms are either mutual or commensal.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Mutualism is an interaction between individuals of different species that results in positive (beneficial) effects on per capita reproduction and/or survival of the interacting populations.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] One well-understood example of mutualism is the interaction between protozoa and methanogenic archaea in the digestive tracts of animals that digest cellulose, such as ruminants and termites.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In these anaerobic environments, protozoa break down plant cellulose to obtain energy.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] This process releases hydrogen as a waste product, but high levels of hydrogen reduce energy production.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] When methanogens convert hydrogen to methane, protozoa benefit from more energy.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In anaerobic protozoa, such as *Plagiopyla frontata*, *Trimyema*, *Heterometopus* and *Metopus contortus*, archaea reside inside the protozoa and consume hydrogen produced in their hydrogenosomes.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaea associate with larger organisms, too.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] For example, the marine archaean *Cenarchaeum symbiosum* is an endosymbiont of the sponge *Axinella mexicana*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Some archaea are commensals, benefiting from an association without helping or harming the other organism.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] For example, the methanogen *Methanobrevibacter smithii* is by far the most common archaean in the human flora, making up about one in ten of the prokaryotes in the human gut.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In termites and in humans, these methanogens may in fact be mutualists, interacting with other microbes in the gut to aid digestion.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaean communities associate with a range of other organisms, such as on the surface of corals, and in the region of soil that surrounds plant roots (the rhizosphere).
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Although Archaea do not have a historical reputation of being pathogens, Archaea are often found with similar genomes to more common pathogens like *E. coli,* showing metabolic links and evolutionary history with today's pathogens.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaea have been inconsistently detected in clinical studies because of the lack of categorization of Archaea into more specific species.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] The reduced genome of *Candidatus* Sukunaarchaeum mirabile suggests it is a specialized parasite highly dependant on its dinoflagellate host.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea, particularly those resistant either to heat or to extremes of acidity and alkalinity, are a source of enzymes that function under these harsh conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] For example, thermostable DNA polymerases, such as the Pfu DNA polymerase from *Pyrococcus furiosus*, revolutionized molecular biology by allowing the polymerase chain reaction to be used in research as a simple and rapid technique for cloning DNA.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In industry, amylases, galactosidases and pullulanases in other species of *Pyrococcus* that function at over 100 °C (212 °F) allow food processing at high temperatures, such as the production of low lactose milk and whey.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Enzymes from these thermophilic archaea also tend to be very stable in organic solvents, allowing their use in environmentally friendly processes in green chemistry that synthesize organic compounds.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] This stability makes them easier to use in structural biology.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Consequently, the counterparts of bacterial or eukaryotic enzymes from extremophile archaea are often used in structural studies.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In contrast with the range of applications of archaean enzymes, the use of the organisms themselves in biotechnology is less developed.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Methanogenic archaea are a vital part of sewage treatment, since they are part of the community of microorganisms that carry out anaerobic digestion and produce biogas.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In mineral processing, acidophilic archaea display promise for the extraction of metals from ores, including gold, cobalt and copper.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] Archaea host a new class of potentially useful antibiotics.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] A few of these archaeocins have been characterized, but hundreds more are believed to exist, especially within Halobacteria and *Sulfolobus*.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] These compounds differ in structure from bacterial antibiotics, so they may have novel modes of action.
[src:biological-organisation/archaea-p02] In addition, they may allow the creation of new selectable markers for use in archaeal molecular biology.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Research in astrobiology comprises three main areas: the study of habitable environments in the Solar System and beyond, the search for planetary biosignatures of past or present extraterrestrial life, and the study of the origin and early evolution of life on Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The field of astrobiology has its origins in the 20th century with the advent of space exploration and the discovery of exoplanets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Early astrobiology research focused on the search for extraterrestrial life and the study of the potential for life to exist on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In the 1960s and 1970s, NASA began its astrobiology pursuits within the Viking program, which was the first US mission to land on Mars and search for signs of life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This mission, along with other early space exploration missions, laid the foundation for the development of astrobiology as a discipline.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Regarding habitable environments, astrobiology investigates potential locations beyond Earth that could support life, such as Mars, Europa, and exoplanets, through research into the extremophiles populating austere environments on Earth, like volcanic and deep sea environments.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Research within this topic is conducted utilising the methodology of the geosciences, especially geobiology, for astrobiological applications.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The search for biosignatures involves the identification of signs of past or present life in the form of organic compounds, isotopic ratios, or microbial fossils.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Research within this topic is conducted utilising the methodology of planetary and environmental science, especially atmospheric science, for astrobiological applications, and is often conducted through remote sensing and in situ missions.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiology also concerns the study of the origin and early evolution of life on Earth to try to understand the conditions that are necessary for life to form on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This research seeks to understand how life emerged from non-living matter and how it evolved to become the diverse array of organisms we see today.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Research within this topic is conducted utilising the methodology of paleosciences, especially paleobiology, for astrobiological applications.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiology is a rapidly developing field with a strong interdisciplinary aspect that holds many challenges and opportunities for scientists.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiology programs and research centres are present in many universities and research institutions around the world, and space agencies like NASA and ESA have dedicated departments and programs for astrobiology research.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The term astrobiology was first proposed by the Russian astronomer Gavriil Tikhov in 1953.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It is etymologically derived from the Greek ἄστρον, "star"; βίος, "life"; and -λογία, *-logia*, "study".
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] A close synonym is exobiology from the Greek Έξω, "external"; βίος, "life"; and -λογία, *-logia*, "study", coined by American molecular biologist Joshua Lederberg; exobiology is considered to have a narrow scope limited to the search for life external to Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The modern field of astrobiology can be traced back to the 1950s and 1960s with the advent of space exploration, when scientists began to seriously consider the possibility of life on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In 1957, the Soviet Union launched Sputnik 1, the first artificial satellite, which marked the beginning of the Space Age.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This event led to an increase in the study of the potential for life on other planets, as scientists began to consider the possibilities opened up by the new technology of space exploration.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In 1959, NASA funded its first exobiology project, and in 1960, NASA founded the Exobiology Program, now one of four main elements of NASA's current Astrobiology Program.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In 1971, NASA funded Project Cyclops, part of the search for extraterrestrial intelligence, to search radio frequencies of the electromagnetic spectrum for interstellar communications transmitted by extraterrestrial life outside the Solar System.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In the 1960s-1970s, NASA established the Viking program, which was the first US mission to land on Mars and search for metabolic signs of present life; the results were inconclusive.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In the 1980s and 1990s, the field began to expand and diversify as new discoveries and technologies emerged.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The discovery of microbial life in extreme environments on Earth, such as deep-sea hydrothermal vents, helped to clarify the feasibility of potential life existing in harsh conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The development of new techniques for the detection of biosignatures, such as the use of stable isotopes, also played a significant role in the evolution of the field.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The contemporary landscape of astrobiology emerged in the early 21st century, focused on utilising Earth and environmental science for applications within comparate space environments.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiological research makes a number of simplifying assumptions when studying the necessary components for planetary habitability.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] These assumptions are based on our current understanding of life on Earth and the conditions under which it can exist.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] As our understanding of life and the potential for it to exist in different environments evolves, these assumptions may change.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiological research concerning the study of habitable environments in the Solar System and beyond utilises methods within the geosciences.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Research within this branch primarily concerns the geobiology of organisms that can survive in extreme environments on Earth, such as in volcanic or deep sea environments, to understand the limits of life, and the conditions under which life might be able to survive on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Emerging astrobiological research concerning the search for planetary biosignatures of past or present extraterrestrial life utilise methodologies within planetary sciences.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Scientists are using data from Mars rover missions to study the composition of the subsurface of Mars, searching for biosignatures of past or present microbial life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Discoveries of surface and subsurface bodies of liquid on moons such as Europa, Titan and Enceladus showed possible habitability zones, making them viable targets for the search for extraterrestrial life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] As of September 2024, missions like *Europa Clipper* and *Dragonfly* are planned to search for biosignatures within these environments.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Scientists search for signals from intelligent extraterrestrial civilizations using radio and optical telescopes within the discipline of extraterrestrial intelligence communications (CETI).
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] CETI focuses on composing and deciphering messages that could theoretically be understood by another technological civilization.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Communication attempts by humans have included broadcasting mathematical languages, pictorial systems such as the Arecibo message, and computational approaches to detecting and deciphering 'natural' language communication.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] While some high-profile scientists, such as Carl Sagan, have advocated the transmission of messages, theoretical physicist Stephen Hawking warned against it, suggesting that aliens may raid Earth for its resources.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Emerging astrobiological research concerning the study of the origin and early evolution of life on Earth utilises methodologies within the palaeosciences.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This includes the role of water in the formation of the first cells and in catalysing chemical reactions.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The systematic search for possible life outside Earth is a valid multidisciplinary scientific endeavor.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] However, hypotheses and predictions as to its existence and origin vary widely, and at the present, the development of hypotheses firmly grounded on science may be considered astrobiology's most concrete practical application.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It has been proposed that viruses are likely to be encountered on other life-bearing planets, and may be present even if there are no biological cells.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] As of 2024, no evidence of extraterrestrial life has been identified.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Examination of the Allan Hills 84001 meteorite, which was recovered in Antarctica in 1984 and originated from Mars, is thought by David McKay, as well as few other scientists, to contain microfossils of extraterrestrial origin; this interpretation is controversial.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Yamato 000593, the second largest meteorite from Mars, was found on Earth in 2000.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] At a microscopic level, spheres are found in the meteorite that are rich in carbon compared to surrounding areas that lack such spheres.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The carbon-rich spheres may have been formed by biotic activity according to some NASA scientists.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Hoover, a scientist with the Marshall Space Flight Center, speculated on the finding of alleged microfossils similar to cyanobacteria in CI1 carbonaceous meteorites in the fringe *Journal of Cosmology*, a story widely reported on by mainstream media.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] However, NASA formally distanced itself from Hoover's claim.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Most astronomy-related astrobiology research falls into the category of extrasolar planet (exoplanet) detection, the hypothesis being that if life arose on Earth, then it could also arise on other planets with similar characteristics.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] To that end, a number of instruments designed to detect Earth-sized exoplanets have been considered, most notably NASA's Terrestrial Planet Finder (TPF) and ESA's Darwin programs, both of which have been cancelled.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] NASA launched the Kepler mission in March 2009, and the French Space Agency launched the COROT space mission in 2006.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] There are also several less ambitious ground-based efforts underway.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The goal of these missions is not only to detect Earth-sized planets but also to directly detect light from the planet so that it may be studied spectroscopically.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] By examining planetary spectra, it would be possible to determine the basic composition of an extrasolar planet's atmosphere and/or surface.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Given this knowledge, it may be possible to assess the likelihood of life being found on that planet.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] A NASA research group, the Virtual Planet Laboratory, is using computer modeling to generate a wide variety of virtual planets to see what they would look like if viewed by TPF or Darwin.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It is hoped that once these missions come online, their spectra can be cross-checked with these virtual planetary spectra for features that might indicate the presence of life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] However, whilst the rationale behind the equation is sound, it is unlikely that the equation will be constrained to reasonable limits of error any time soon.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The problem with the formula is that it is not used to generate or support hypotheses because it contains factors that can never be verified.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The first term, ***R****, number of stars, is generally constrained within a few orders of magnitude.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The second and third terms, *fp*, stars with planets and *fe*, planets with habitable conditions, are being evaluated for the star's neighborhood.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Drake originally formulated the equation merely as an agenda for discussion at the Green Bank conference, but some applications of the formula had been taken literally and related to simplistic or pseudoscientific arguments.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Another associated topic is the Fermi paradox, which suggests that if intelligent life is common in the universe, then there should be obvious signs of it.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Another active research area in astrobiology is planetary system formation.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It has been suggested that the peculiarities of the Solar System (for example, the presence of Jupiter as a protective shield) may have greatly increased the probability of intelligent life arising on Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Biology cannot state that a process or phenomenon, by being mathematically possible, has to exist forcibly in an extraterrestrial body.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Biologists specify what is speculative and what is not.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Until the 1970s, life was thought to be entirely dependent on energy from the Sun.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Plants on Earth's surface capture energy from sunlight to photosynthesize sugars from carbon dioxide and water, releasing oxygen in the process that is then consumed by oxygen-respiring organisms, passing their energy up the food chain.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Even life in the ocean depths, where sunlight cannot reach, was thought to obtain its nourishment either from consuming organic detritus rained down from the surface waters or from eating animals that did.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The world's ability to support life was thought to depend on its access to sunlight.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] However, in 1977, during an exploratory dive to the Galapagos Rift in the deep-sea exploration submersible *Alvin*, scientists discovered colonies of giant tube worms, clams, crustaceans, mussels, and other assorted creatures clustered around undersea volcanic features known as black smokers.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] These creatures thrive despite having no access to sunlight, and it was soon discovered that they form an entirely independent ecosystem.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Other lifeforms entirely decoupled from the energy from sunlight are green sulfur bacteria which are capturing geothermal light for anoxygenic photosynthesis or bacteria running chemolithoautotrophy based on the radioactive decay of uranium.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This chemosynthesis revolutionized the study of biology and astrobiology by revealing that life need not be sunlight-dependent; it only requires water and an energy gradient in order to exist.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Biologists have found extremophiles that thrive in ice, boiling water, acid, alkali, the water core of nuclear reactors, salt crystals, toxic waste and in a range of other extreme habitats that were previously thought to be inhospitable for life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This opened up a new avenue in astrobiology by massively expanding the number of possible extraterrestrial habitats.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Characterization of these organisms, their environments and their evolutionary pathways, is considered a crucial component to understanding how life might evolve elsewhere in the universe.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] While tardigrades are not considered true extremophiles, they are considered extremotolerant microorganisms that have contributed to the field of astrobiology.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Their extreme radiation tolerance and presence of DNA protection proteins may provide answers as to whether life can survive away from the protection of the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In addition to their role as analogues for potential extraterrestrial life, extremophiles are also being investigated for their potential use in space biotechnology and in in-situ resource utilization (ISRU).
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Microorganisms capable of biomining and bioleaching, for example, could support the extraction of metals and nutrients from planetary regolith or asteroid material, contributing to sustainable human exploration.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Such applications highlight that astrobiology is not only concerned with detecting life elsewhere but also with harnessing biological processes to enable space exploration.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Tonietti *et al.* (2023) have discussed the relevance of biomining and bioleaching research within the broader framework of astrobiology and ISRU strategies.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Cockell *et al.* (2020) demonstrated in the International Space Station BioRock experiment that rare earth elements can be bioleached from basalt under microgravity and Mars gravity conditions, confirming that microbial metabolisms can operate in extraterrestrial environments.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Santomartino *et al.* (2022) outlined the principles of space biomining, including bioleaching, soil formation, waste recycling, and energy production, emphasizing the role of microorganisms as "the smallest space miners".
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] A subsequent review further developed a roadmap for sustainable space exploration based on microbial processes such as biomining, bioremediation, and biomanufacturing.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] More broadly, the concept of "applied astrobiology" has been proposed as an integrated framework that connects fundamental questions about life in the universe with biotechnological applications for human space exploration.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In addition to extremophile research, quantum-chemical studies have shown that organic molecules produced by living systems generally display narrower HOMO–LUMO gaps than those formed abiotically, with this distinction sharpened among more water-soluble compounds.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Such gap measurements are thus emerging as a promising electronic biosignature for distinguishing biotic from abiotic chemistries in future life-detection missions.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Jupiter's moon, Europa, and Saturn's moon, Enceladus, are now considered the most likely locations for extant extraterrestrial life in the Solar System due to their subsurface water oceans where radiogenic and tidal heating enables liquid water to exist.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The origin of life, known as abiogenesis, distinct from the evolution of life, is another ongoing field of research.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Oparin and Haldane postulated that the conditions on the early Earth were conducive to the formation of organic compounds from inorganic elements and thus to the formation of many of the chemicals common to all forms of life we see today.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The study of this process, known as prebiotic chemistry, has made some progress, but it is still unclear whether or not life could have formed in such a manner on Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The alternative hypothesis of panspermia is that the first elements of life may have formed on another planet with even more favorable conditions (or even in interstellar space, asteroids, etc.) and then have been carried over to Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organic compounds ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic-aliphatic structure") that could be created naturally, and rapidly, by stars.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] More than 20% of the carbon in the universe may be associated with polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), possible starting materials for the formation of life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] PAHs seem to have been formed shortly after the Big Bang, are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] PAHs are subjected to interstellar medium conditions and are transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation and hydroxylation, to more complex organics—"a step along the path toward amino acids and nucleotides, the raw materials of proteins and DNA, respectively".
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] In October 2020, astronomers proposed the idea of detecting life on distant planets by studying the shadows of trees at certain times of the day to find patterns that could be detected through observation of exoplanets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] David Grinspoon called astrobiology a field of natural philosophy.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiology intersects with philosophy by raising questions about the nature and existence of life beyond Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Dunér has emphasized philosophy of astrobiology as an ongoing existential exercise in individual and collective self-understanding, whose major task is constructing and debating concepts such as the concept of life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Persson also emphasized key philosophical questions in astrobiology.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] They include ethical justification of resources, the question of life in general, the epistemological issues and knowledge about being alone in the universe, ethics towards extraterrestrial life, the question of politics and governing uninhabited worlds, along with questions of ecology.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] For von Hegner, the question of astrobiology and the possibility of astrophilosophy differs.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] For him, the discipline needs to bifurcate into astrobiology and astrophilosophy since discussions made possible by astrobiology, but which have been astrophilosophical in nature, have existed as long as there have been discussions about extraterrestrial life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrobiology is a self-corrective interaction among observation, hypothesis, experiment, and theory, pertaining to the exploration of all natural phenomena.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Astrophilosophy consists of methods of dialectic analysis and logical argumentation, pertaining to the clarification of the nature of reality. Šekrst argues that astrobiology requires the affirmation of astrophilosophy, but not as a separate cognate to astrobiology.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The stance of conceptual speciesm, according to Šekrst, permeates astrobiology since the very name astrobiology tries to talk about not just biology, but about life in a general way, which includes terrestrial life as a subset.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This leads us to either redefine philosophy, or consider the need for astrophilosophy as a more general discipline, to which philosophy is just a subset that deals with questions such as the nature of the human mind and other anthropocentric questions.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Most of the philosophy of astrobiology deals with two main questions: the question of life and the ethics of space exploration.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Kolb specifically emphasizes the question of viruses, for which the question whether they are alive or not is based on the definitions of life that include self-replication.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Schneider tried to defined exo-life, but concluded that we often start with our own prejudices and that defining extraterrestrial life seems futile using human concepts.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] For Dick, astrobiology relies on metaphysical assumption that there is extraterrestrial life, which reaffirms questions in the philosophy of cosmology, such as fine-tuning or the anthropic principle.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The Rare Earth hypothesis postulates that multicellular life forms found on Earth may actually be more of a rarity than scientists assume.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It provides a possible answer to the Fermi paradox which wonders: if extraterrestrial aliens are common, why are they not obvious?
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It is apparently in opposition to the principle of mediocrity, assumed by famed astronomers Frank Drake, Carl Sagan, and others.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The principle of mediocrity suggests that life on Earth is not exceptional, and it is more than likely to be found on innumerable other worlds.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Research into the environmental limits of life and the workings of extreme ecosystems is ongoing, enabling researchers to better predict what planetary environments might be most likely to harbor life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Missions such as the *Phoenix* lander, Mars Science Laboratory, ExoMars, Mars 2020 rover to Mars, and the *Cassini* probe to Saturn's moons aim to further explore the possibilities of life on other planets in the Solar System.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The two Viking landers each carried four types of biological experiments to the surface of Mars in the late 1970s.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] These were the only Mars landers to carry out experiments looking specifically for metabolism by current microbial life on Mars.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The landers used a robotic arm to collect soil samples into sealed test containers on the craft.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The two landers were identical, so the same tests were carried out at two places on Mars' surface; *Viking 1* near the equator and *Viking 2* further north.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The result was inconclusive, and is still disputed by some scientists.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Norman Horowitz was the chief of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory bioscience section for the Mariner and Viking missions from 1965 to 1976.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Horowitz considered that the great versatility of the carbon atom makes it the element most likely to provide solutions, even exotic solutions, to the problems of survival of life on other planets.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] However, he also considered that the conditions found on Mars were incompatible with carbon based life.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] EXPOSE is a multi-user facility mounted in 2008 outside the International Space Station dedicated to astrobiology.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] EXPOSE was developed by the European Space Agency (ESA) for long-term spaceflights that allow exposure of organic chemicals and biological samples to outer space in low Earth orbit.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The Mars Science Laboratory (MSL) mission landed the *Curiosity* rover that is currently in operation on Mars.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It was launched 26 November 2011, and landed at Gale Crater on 6 August 2012.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The *Tanpopo* mission is an orbital astrobiology experiment investigating the potential interplanetary transfer of life, organic compounds, and possible terrestrial particles in the low Earth orbit.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The purpose is to assess the panspermia hypothesis and the possibility of natural interplanetary transport of microbial life as well as prebiotic organic compounds.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Early mission results show evidence that some clumps of microorganism can survive for at least one year in space.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] This may support the idea that clumps greater than 0.5 millimeters of microorganisms could be one way for life to spread from planet to planet.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] Mars 2020 successfully landed its rover *Perseverance* in Jezero Crater on 18 February 2021.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] It will investigate environments on Mars relevant to astrobiology, investigate its surface geological processes and history, including the assessment of its past habitability and potential for preservation of biosignatures and biomolecules within accessible geological materials.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The Science Definition Team is proposing the rover collect and package at least 31 samples of rock cores and soil for a later mission to bring back for more definitive analysis in laboratories on Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/astrobiology] The rover could make measurements and technology demonstrations to help designers of a human expedition understand any hazards posed by Martian dust and demonstrate how to collect carbon dioxide (CO2), which could be a resource for making molecular oxygen (O2) and rocket fuel.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:biological-organisation/atmosphere-of-earth] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
